post_text: We are changing the way we have Pep-Rallies this year! I want to thank everyone for being so flexible as we continue to keep student and staff safety in mind as we begin the new school year. With that being said, we are going to move our Friday Pep-Rallies to Wednesday Nights at the Football Stadium. We will have our First Pep-Rally Under the Lights this Wednesday at 8:30 PM. We will have seats sectioned off for parents to attend. We will place the Football Players, Cheerleaders, and Band on the Field. We will begin the Pep-Rally Promptly at 8:30 PM. Come out and support our Jackrabbits!
text: We are changing the way we have Pep-Rallies this year! I want to thank everyone for being so flexible as we continue to keep student and staff safety in mind as we begin the new school year. post_text: Ralls HS had a great day of Professional Development focused on adapting our educational practices towards success. We had the pleasure of learning from the owners of Happy’s Shaved Ice, Bubble Tea and Smoothies! Our new District Counselor, Ms. Murry, interviewed the owners Kaydi and Tyler and was able to get some great insight into their success! They provided great advice for other business owners as well as educators on having the right mentality on being able to adopt and adapt as they worked through overcoming the struggles and barriers of being a small business owner through these tough times! They spoke of "evolving out of it if it ain't working!". We were able to apply many of their beliefs into our world of education. They were also kind enough to provide our staff with a free shaved ice! Thanks Happy's!!!

After interviews concluded on Tuesday, June 2nd, 2020, the RISD Board of Trustees voted unanimously to name Dr. Maxwell and begin the mandatory 21-day waiting period.
We are excited to welcome Dr. Maxwell and his family to the community of Ralls and Jackrabbit Country!

post_text:
Message from Ralls Public Library:

SUMMER READING has started at the Ralls Public Library. Things are a little different but if you come by and visit, get signed up, and start checking out books, you can be a part of the reading crowd. For every 5 books every child reads, they will earn a small gift. At the end of July, the one with most books read receives the Gold Rabbit Award and a special prize.
EVERY WEDNESDAY in June we will have a live story hour at 10:30 in the morning. If you listen in, come to the Library, tell us a little about the book, such as title, or names of characters, or your favorite part, you can also get a small gift.
Best of all, if you read, you make yourself better.
We are trying to build a castle on the window, so for every book you read, you can add a brick to the castle wall. Come by the Library and find out what its all about. Share this post, please.
If you have a mask, please wear it in the Library, we are practicing social distancing, and we have sanitizer for your hands when you come.
Come in and IMAGINE YOUR STORY!

post_text:
“If you are neutral in the face of injustice, you have chosen the side of the oppressor.” -Desmond Tutu-
Ralls ISD stands with our students, families and community members who have experienced any kind of systemic racism, systemic oppression, or any other kind of discrimination. We are experiencing troubling times in our world and we want to help spread love. We can help shine light on the good in all people and we also want to be the light for those around us by the way we treat one another, and stand for those who are not treated how they should be. Take the time today to talk to your children and have open and honest conversations about seeing someone’s value based on what they’re about on the inside as opposed to judging them based on what they see on the outside. We want to help fight the hate with the love that we are capable of spreading. We love our community and we are here for each and every one of you. #BlackOutTuesday #BeTheLight #JackrabbitStrong #FearTheEars
Instagram: Ralls_ISD

Ralls ISD has an opportunity to partner with Community in Schools through a grant. Please take time to complete the survey. We want to gather as much information as we can to ensure we get an accurate picture of our communities' needs and assets. The data gathered from the survey will inform both the implementation grant proposal we submit to the national CIS office requesting funds to expand CIS services to Ralls ISD as well as the campus plans we implement at each school if funded.
Surveys need to be completed by Monday, June 1st.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSc1lh1NoSVdSLaC-RfHQkn-XISZA3fmC2vh6ITn1KsW-KJX1A/viewform?usp=sf_link

Does your child receive special education services? If yes, this is a reminder that it is time for the Parent Involvement Survey being conducted by the Texas Education Agency (TEA)!

If your child receiving special education services was selected as part of this year’s survey effort, you should have received an email invitation containing your unique PIN needed to complete the survey. You can go to www.ParentSurveyTX.com and complete the survey online. If you cannot find your PIN, or need assistance to complete the survey, call (512) 685-2692 or toll-free at (877) 328-0884 ext. 109.

Please be sure to complete the survey by May 22.

Thank you for your participation.

Ralls ISD

post_text:
GRADUATION ANNOUNCEMENT for HS and REC Graduations!!!

As we have made plans for Graduation, keep in mind that there are certain aspects that are completely out of our control. We had a couple of plans in mind when we began the process of planning this ceremony; from a completely virtual style graduation, and then drive-by style graduation ceremony where everyone stayed in their vehicles (similar to how we did the Honor Graduates Ceremony), to what we now have will have in place.

The 3 biggest announcements for this upcoming graduation ceremony will be:
1. We are now allowed to have an in-person graduation ceremony outside!
2. Graduates will ONLY be allowed to bring 5 guests. Each graduate and their guests will have seats on the football field. We will proceed with a formal graduation ceremony similar to what we have done in the past with a couple of tweaks.
3. Nobody else will be allowed into the stadium. There will not be anyone allowed in the stands. There will not be anyone standing along the fence inside the stadium. No one else will be allowed into the stadium.

post_text:
Attention REC Graduates and Family:

With the announcement made by Governor Abbot on Tuesday, May 5th, Ralls ISD will continue forward with the original date of an outdoor Graduation on Friday, May 15th at 8 PM planned at Doc Mize Stadium. We will continue to stay current on all local and state guidelines to ensure we adhere to all social distancing mandates. The Graduation will also be streamed live through Ralls ISD Facebook Live for those who are not able to attend. Ralls ISD will release additional ceremony details, guest limitations, and weather contingency plans once the plans have been finalized. We are working to make this a memorable graduation for our students that are very deserving of this recognition! Just as a reminder, this date and time are for our REC graduates. The Ralls High School graduation will be held Thursday, May 21st. #JackrabbitStrong #FearTheEars

Seniors and Senior Parents!!!!
We have rented a “Class of 2020” sign from Sign Dreamers for you to come and take a picture in your cap and gown! (Don’t worry... you won’t look as good as the guy in the photo!). This will be on Wednesday, May 6th. Social Distancing Guidelines will be followed.

These letters will be placed in the front lawn at the HS. They will be available for you starting at 9 AM. You are free to take pictures as you want throughout the day. However, we will be taking pictures starting at 6:30 PM until 8 PM. We have 45 Students that will need their picture taken and we need to maintain Social Distancing throughout this time. We will have time slots for everyone.

So, here are the instructions:
1. Arrive during your time slot
2. Be in dress code
3. Wear your Cap and Gown for this picture. If you received Honor Cords, wear those as well.

Time Slots: We have emailed time slots to each Senior. Check Your Email.
6:30 - REC Students, HS Group 1
6:45 - HS Group 2
7:00 - HS Group 3
7:15 - HS Group 4
7:30 - HS Group 5

post_text: On Friday Night, we were able to honor our Senior Softball and Baseball Players at each of their respective fields. Even though this season was cut short, we are still grateful for the dedication and time they invested in our programs over the past 4 years. We are disappointed that we were not able to complete the season, but we are very proud of the efforts and sacrifices that these young men and women have given. We honored these outstanding student athletes along with their parents. So on behalf of Ralls ISD, we would like to thank you for sharing your precious children with us on this amazing journey we have called life the past 4 years!

Some of our 10th Grade Lady Rabbits wanted to share a video message of hope and inspiration as they spent some time picking up trash around town.

“Be the Light”
“We fall, we break, we fail. But then, we rise, we heal, we overcome.”
“Imagine with all your mind. Believe with all your heart. Achieve with all your might.”
“Start from nothing. Stop for nothing.”
“Be fearless in the pursuit of what sets your soul on fire.”
“Nothing can dim the light that shines within.”
“Believe you can.”

#JackrabbitStrong #FearTheEars

Congratulations to our FCCLA Students Lexi Escobar, Chris Luna and Cainyn Hair for placing 1st!!! Even though we were unable to go and compete at the State FCCLA conference, they used the scores and rubrics from the Regional conferences to determine what places students would have received at state.

Based on our score from Regionals, the Toys that Teach Proficiency Event Team, Lexi, Chris, and Cainyn placed 1st!!!

We are saddened that the students did not have the opportunity to go and compete in person but we are so proud of how they did! Congrats to Ms. Ashley Carpenter as well for guiding them on this journey. Great job!!!

post_text: Pete Christy features former Ralls AD Billy Villarreal, or Coach V as he is known around here! Coach V was a great Coach, but an even better mentor, role model and friend to many in the Ralls Community.
shared_text:
Pete Christy KCBD
April 27 at 7:57 PM ·

Call a Coach:

Today I called former Ralls football/baseball coach Billy Villarreal. We had a great 18 minute conversation.

Coach V was there with the Jackrabbits 1998-2009.

He told me his highlight in Ralls was the 07-08 football seasons when they got back in playoffs and getting a playoff win.

In June of 2012, Billy V became the Slaton baseball coach.

He got out of coaching in 2014 and now he works for New York Life, helping folks with life insurance and retirement.

He works with a lot of current coaches.

We have kept a strong friendship over the years.

The photo is from a long time ago when we did an I Beat Pete out at Ralls. I told coach he looks like he’s 16 like current principal Miguel Salazar.

Every day I decided I will call a coach and talk to him or her about their family and then their team and what’s going on in the world so I could encourage an encourager.

This isn’t Text a Coach, but Call a Coach.

The art of conversation is being lost. I encourage you to call someone today and touch base and check on them and lift their spirits.

Every day I decided I will call a coach and talk to him or her about their family and then their team and what’s going on in the world so I could encourage an encourager.

post_text:
Even through these tough times, our Coaches and Teachers are doing what they always do... taking on a challenge and fighting to make it work! They continue to bring hope and show love to their students even though they aren’t in our presence. As a Jackrabbit Family, we continue to practice Social Distancing, but it will take something far greater than COVID-19 to keep us from each other! We are missing our students terribly, but we continue to stay #jackrabbitstrong! Here is an insight into our SB team visiting and cheering each other up!

Today our softball team met over Zoom. Coach Miller and Coach Reagan really do miss their team. “Being separated during this time is difficult, but we are staying strong and connected. It was so heartwarming to see our team and get to talk to them a little bit! Hopefully, we will have a video posted soon on how we are staying sharp and working on our softball skills.” states Coach Reagan. (They are missing Lexi and Lorna in their picture.)

So a huge thanks to all our Teachers and Coaches!
text:
Even through these tough times, our Coaches and Teachers are doing what they always do... taking on a challenge and fighting to make it work! They continue to bring hope and show love to their students even though they aren’t in our presence. As a Jackrabbit Family, we continue to practice Social Distancing, but it will take something far greater than COVID-19 to keep us from each other! We are missing our students terribly, but we continue to stay #jackrabbitstrong! Here is an insight into our SB team visiting and cheering each other up!

Today our softball team met over Zoom. Coach Miller and Coach Reagan really do miss their team. “Being separated during this time is difficult, but we are staying strong and connected. It was so heartwarming to see our team and get to talk to them a little bit! Hopefully, we will have a video posted soon on how we are staying sharp and working on our softball skills.” states Coach Reagan. (They are missing Lexi and Lorna in their picture.)

So a huge thanks to all our Teachers and Coaches!

We together will get through this and come back stronger than ever.

Thank you,

Mr. Wade

Junior Class

We wanted to let everyone know what to do about the Coke selling fundraiser. In the interest of our student safety, we do not believe that distributing drinks in our current health situation as a wise idea. We would like students to either practice social distancing and return any money for drink orders or take any money to the high school for the staff to return. While we know this is not the simplest or easiest option for the fundraiser, we are wanting to make a decision that is best for the health and safety of our students. If we are able to come back to school this semester with enough time to successfully complete the fundraiser, we will attempt this again. We appreciate your willingness to take part in the fundraiser and please feel free to email Mr. Herron (mherron@rallsisd.org) if you have any questions.

Thanks for your patience

Ralls High School Staff

post_text: Ralls Middle School eighth grade students Ashley Pina and Justin Zavala were recently named to the Whataburger Winner’s Circle. The Winner’s Circle is a joint effort between Whataburger and Texas Tech University to reward middle school students across the state for contributions to their schools, their families and their communities in addition to academic achievements and school involvement. The award seeks to recognize behaviors and actions that are positive, such as attending class on time, improving academically, being a good citizen, completing all their homework, being respectful in class, etc. As a Whataburger Winner’s Circle recipient, the students will receive four free Texas Tech Baseball game tickets, four free Whataburgers, a winner’s circle T-shirt and a certificate. They will also be recognized at the Tech baseball game! Congratulations to these two outstanding kiddos!

Ralls ISD, the Texas Education Agency, and the Texas Department of State Health Services are monitoring the spread of the Coronavirus Disease and plans are in place if an outbreak occurs in our area. Health officials believe the risk to our school community is low at this time. Please feel free to visit the DSHS website for up to date information on this disease and how to prevent the spread of germs. You can access the website at:

https://dshs.texas.gov/coronavirus

Our staff members are working carefully to encourage simple and effective habits of frequent hand washing, covering every cough/sneeze, and cleaning classroom tables/surfaces frequently. This is important not just to help prevent the spread of coronavirus, but to help prevent the spread of other infections (common cold, flu, strep) that can lead to illness and absences.

Thank you for your support of our district, our students and our staff.

Mr. Wade

post_text:
Ralls Elementary Parents:
Safety is our top priority for all students and staff so just a quick reminder to please not drive into the parking lot in the mornings to drop off your children. You can park across the street and your child can use the crosswalk or you are more than welcome to walk them in. Another option is to drive around the playground and let them enter through the southeast doors. We have buses unloading and many children walking across the parking lot in the morning and it is usually dark so it can become very dangerous. Thank you so much for your attention to this issue.

post_text:
Dear students and parents that are showing livestock at next weeks County Show:
The county rules state that if you want to sell your animal at the Premium Sale, all students must attend a workday at the county barn in Crosbyton. This Sunday, January 12 at 1:00 p.m. is your last chance to get it done. Our County Show is next week January 15-18. If you need your animals clipped, we will do it on Monday and Tuesday next week after school. All animals must be washed and dried before we clip. The weight limit is 155-270 for pigs. If you need help clipping, please let Mr. French know this week.

post_text: Ralls Middle School has recently opened our RMS Jackrabbit Store for this year. The students earn Jackrabbit Bucks for good behavior, showing kindness, and improving academically. They get to spend their bucks to shop in our store for their families for Christmas and buy some goodies for themselves as well. When they are shopping for others- we even gift wrap! Its been a huge success so far and we wanted to share some of these awesome pictures with our community. Thank you Mrs. Rosie Martinez for setting up our store! We also want to say a special THANK YOU to all of our fellow faculty members at RISD and Ralls community members that have donated this year to help us get our store up and running. #itsgreattobeajackrabbit #rallsmiddleschool #ittakesavillage

post_text:
Congratulations to Kaleb Salazar and Joe Sanchez for making Academic All-State for football. This is quite an accomplishment. We also want to thank their families for pushing them to achieve success at a high level both athletically and academically!

Texas High School Coaches Association Academic All-State in Football:
Kaleb Salazar 1st Team
Joe Sanchez 2nd Team

The THSCA Academic All-State Teams recognize high school athletes who excel in the following categories: GPA, class rank and ACT/SAT score. The students are being recognized as a team member based on their scores in these categories. We applaud them for their commitment and dedication to perform with the highest of excellence academically and on the field or court. To be nominated for Academic All-State, a student must be:
An athlete, student trainer or manager in good standing with the team
Of good moral character
A senior
Have an overall grade point average of 92 or above (including courses from grades 9-11 and courses completed from grade 12).

post_text:
Attention Ralls Elementary and Ralls Middle School Parents:

Deadline to complete the survey is November 29th.

You should have received your 2nd letter this week about a survey we are asking you to complete online.

The letter stated:
The Center for Effective Schools will begin administering feedback surveys to families across the state. Your views on matters like the safety of your child at school, the way students are taught, and your and your child’s connection to school are crucial. These surveys will give you a unique opportunity to provide anonymous feedback about your experience in these areas and others.
The survey window will be from October 14th to November 29th. We are asking you to complete this survey and help the leadership at both of the campuses to make improvements.
The letter provided a link to the brief 10-minute survey. If you have any questions, please contact Macy Cavazos, mcavazos@rallsisd.org.
We look forward to your input. Thank you for your time!

post_text: Coach Ebeling’s class took a VR Tour of Rome today in World Geography using VR Goggles. These Virtual Reality Goggles were a donation made to Ralls ISD by the ladies at Delta Kappa Gamma Society. DKG promotes professional and personal growth of women educators and excellence in education. Ralls HS students enjoyed seeing some historical landmarks and learning about Rome in “The Virtual World”! Huge thanks to Coach Ebeling for preparing this lesson for his students as I think the students really enjoyed the it! They have even asked him to prepare more lessons in the future with the VR headsets. Coach Ebeling used a combination of students phones, the VR Goggles (donated by DKG) and YouTube to allow the students to travel to Rome.... without having to leave the classroom!

post_text: Today we laid to rest a dear member of the Ralls ISD family, Ms. Leigh Gregory. Ms. Gregory was serving as a Special Education Teacher at Ralls Elementary, a position that she served with great love and care. She has served many students over the years as she began her career in Springfield, Colorado and luckily for us, she spent most of her career here at Ralls Elementary. She planted many seeds of love throughout her career, a legacy that will live through many of our students in our community for years to come. She has spent her career serving others. She was a great woman, mother, grandmother, co-worker and friend who cared deeply for her children, grandchildren, school children, friends and family. She leaves behind a legacy of strength, kindness, compassion and love. She was a great asset to our school, to our community and to her family and will be dearly missed. Please continue to keep her family in your thoughts and prayers.

Our 1st place winner was Charles Gwinn... and will receive a $25 Nike Gift Card (as well as a big jar full of 3,380 pieces of candy corn)!!! Samuel Salinas was a very close 2nd and Kaleb Salazar was 3rd! Both received a snack for their efforts. It’s a great day to be Drug Free... and as always a great day to be a Mighty Jackrabbit!

post_text:
Attention Ralls Elementary and Ralls Middle School Parents:

Last week, you should have received a letter about a survey we are asking you to complete online.
The letter stated:
The Center for Effective Schools will begin administering feedback surveys to families across the state. Your views on matters like the safety of your child at school, the way students are taught, and your and your child’s connection to school are crucial. These surveys will give you a unique opportunity to provide anonymous feedback about your experience in these areas and others.
The survey window will be from October 14th to November 29th. We are asking you to complete this survey and help the leadership at both of the campuses to make improvements.
The letter provided a link to the brief 10-minute survey. If you have any questions, please contact Macy Cavazos, mcavazos@rallsisd.org.
We look forward to your input. Thank you for your time!

post_text: Band Results from the UIL Marching Contest.......... led by Mr. Walker and Mr. Aguirre, with Senior Drum Majors Santana Rivera and Mia Salas........ All 1’s!!!!! What a Great Day to be a Jackrabbit!!! A huge thanks to our Band Director Mr. Walker for his dedication and love for our kids. Also, to our Assistant Band Director Mr. Aguirre (Mr. A!), for jumping right in and helping to keep our winning tradition alive! And last, and not least, to our Seniors for their dedication to our program. Their leadership will be missed next marching season! They did a great job performing today for their last performance as members of the Ralls Jackrabbit Marching Band!!! Thanks to Raiyah Appleton, Joaquin Cavazos, Mercedes Garcia, Adrianna Guzman, Austin Ledesma, Kylie Lopez, Ana Lozano, Celyce Martinez, Santana Rivera, Mia Salas, Leo Santiago, Angel Sotelo, and Ethan Villanueva.

post_text: Ralls High School Band Director, Kenneth Walker was presented with the Cotton Patch Cafe “Hometown Heroes Award” this morning! Cotton Patch Cafe is a great company that has made it part of their mission to recognize community members that go the extra mile for their community. Cotton Patch Cafe representative Glen Piner, Area Director, arrived to quite the scene as the Ralls High School and Middle School students lined the streets between the 2 schools. Ralls Community member Elida Rodriguez nominated Mr. Walker for the award and wrote of his commitment to the students and community of Ralls through his role as the Band Director. Mr. Walker has been an inspiration to us all, and we couldn’t think of a more deserving “hometown hero” to recognize during this time! He was presented a $1,000 Check to use for the school, and will receive Cotton Patch food for a year!!! Congratulations Mr. Walker!!!

post_text: The Eighth Grade College and Career Readiness class attended the Career Expo in Lubbock, TX. Monday, September 30, 2019. The event was sponsored by the Texas Workforce Commission. About 30 booths were set up to introduce students to a wide variety of possible careers and to answer the students' questions about them. Most of their questions were about the level of education required, as well as the salary and benefits they could expect. There were a few hands-on booths and live demonstrations, including one using a transformer to show what could happen if you came in contact with electrical power lines. Some of the students were interviewed on a live radio broadcast and all of them participated in a personal finance simulation. It is sometimes difficult to imagine possibilities you don’t know exist. This was a good opportunity to expose the kids to occupations they may have not ever considered.

post_text: Ralls AP Senior English class helped to deliver a powerful reading of the timeline of events from September 11th, 2001. A message filled with fear and hope. A hope that we never forget the lives that were lost on that dreadful day, and how our country came to together towards a common fight. We are now living in a world where our children only know of this day because of the stories that are told, and not by their own perspective of the sequence of events from that day. It changed our country forever, and our hope is to help them remember that we must remain united as a country, and to honor those around us that are willing to make the ultimate sacrifice. Men and women of our Armed services and First Responders, that put their own lives at risk so that we can enjoy ours. #NeverForget

post_text:
Friday was life event day in Mr. G's Financial Math Class! These seniors are learning how random life events affect their financial situation. Some examples include: having a child, inheriting a gift, and today's example, having your identity stolen. Every student in the class has a fixed income and learn how to balance their monthly bills while trying to save up for their retirement and take vacations.
These students are all in the process of interviewing for their job in the class to practice their job interview skills. A special thanks to Mr. G for helping these seniors learn important life skills before they graduate!

post_text: Watch the video! Mental Health Awareness: Last spring, we were approached by Erin Cargile KXAN of Austin in regards to Mental Health and how schools utilize their resources to provide the support needed to help students. The TWITR project they reference is a program that provides additional support for area schools in dealing with mental health. We were honored to visit with them about the ways in which we utilize our resources to provide our students with the support needed. We are proud to have such a loving and caring staff, and want to take this opportunity to thank them for all that they do! We want students at Ralls ISD to know that asking for help is not a sign of weakness, rather it is a sign of strength. We encourage our students to be open about asking for help.
